This year women received Nobel Prizes in all categories except Physics
Five women, which is a record number, were awarded this year's Nobel Prizes in specialized categories and literature by King Charles XVI Gustav of Sweden in Stockholm today.
In addition to the four scientists, a German writer of Romanian origin, Herta Müller, was also among the winners.
The Nobel Prize in Medicine was awarded to two American biologists, Elizabeth Blackburn and Carol Greider, as well as their compatriot Jack Szostak for research in the field of chromosomes.
The Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Israeli Ada Jonath and Americans Venkatraman Ramakrishna and Thomas Steitz for explaining the structure and function of ribosomes.
The latest prize, the Nobel Prize in Economics, was awarded to Elinor Ostrom and her compatriot Oliver Williamson for their analysis of an economic report.
The only specialized category, without an award-winning woman, was Physics.
This award was awarded today to scientists Charles Kao for research in the field of optical cables, and George Smith with Willard Boyle for the invention of the CCD chip, which forms the basis of all digital cameras, faxes or telescopes.
Each laureate collected the diploma, Nobel medal and certificate of the money received.
This sum in each category is up to ten million Swedish kronor (approximately 25 million Czech kronor).
In the event that there are several winners in each category, the prize is distributed to each other.
The traditionally long-awaited Nobel Peace Prize was presented to U.S. President Barack Obama in Oslo, Norway, this afternoon.
In his speech he acknowledged the controversy of having been awarded, since he is at the beginning of his career and also at the head of a country that participates in two wars: in Iraq and in Afghanistan.
