Management Revolution or the End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of employees adhering to "values" determined from above as before it was a question of imposing on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to market conquest strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to the factors of customer preference is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) “requires that all parties involved ... have a proactive conduct and a forward-looking vision”; it needs on the part of employees a commitment that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we called for a management revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative usefulness
Will internal opinion polls, such as the Orange employee questionnaire, incite the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did!
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology mechanistically.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the old behaviorist theory that the American “neurosciences” recently revived, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the “commands” (sic) of executive engagement, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management posture, unsuited to today’s world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies implies adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating in all reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make part of their dreams, ambitions and projects come true.
Today, only studies from Motivational Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of mobilisation factors, business managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their “social performance” and relocate human resource management “on the spot”.
In this way, they create a favourable terrain for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo Speech: Obama Receives Right-Wing Praise for ‘Just War’
On Friday, the American right, pleased that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize had defended the concept of "just war" against America's enemies, hailed the speech Obama had delivered on Thursday.
The conservatives, who had discredited the award to Obama on October 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate during the 2008 election.
I loved what she said, said Ms. Palin, a leading figure in the right wing of the Republican party, adding that she herself had addressed the issue of war "sometimes necessary" in her recently published memoirs.
In my opinion, war is, of course, the last thing Americans want to be forced to do, but it is necessary.
The terrorists must be stopped, he said.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, on Thursday in Oslo dedicated himself to justifying the use of force, a way of explaining his decision to send 30,000 more troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really very good, the former Speaker of the House of Representatives rejoiced, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential words.
At times, the speech seemed very historic to me, Gingrich said, during an interview on the radio show "The Takeaway."
The former elected representative, who some see as a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, was pleased to hear from “a left-wing president” when he reminded Nobel committee members “that they would not be free nor could they hand over a peace prize if the use of force did not exist.”
According to Michael Gerson, author of George W. Bush’s speeches and current Washington Post columnist, Obama delivered “a very American speech.”
