Among the few unconvinced right-wingers, a Bush-era falcon, former U.N. ambassador John Bolton called the speech "monotonous, pretentious, and uninspired" on the National Review Online website.
To the left of the president, Democratic Rep. Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When we cover war with the notion of justice, it is easy to justify the massacre of innocents, he warned.
However, the centre-left press praised the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while still believing that Obama received the Nobel Prize prematurely, called his speech "overproduction" especially for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech “should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions in the fight against conflict, poverty and oppression,” the California newspaper enthusiastically commented.
Obama “pronounced the speech that was necessary,” the New York Times estimated, judging it “both gloomy and uplifting.”
