Turkish court dissolves pro-Kurdish party, decision with grave consequences
Turkey's Constitutional Court ruled Friday in favor of the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that immediately sparked outbursts of anger in the Kurdish community, the country's southeast and Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community trying to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it had become the "focus of activities that harmed the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," the president of the court, Hasim Kiliç, told reporters after four days of deliberations.
