In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania and attending a secondary school.
An ordinary girl.
If it weren't for those images and voices.
Sometimes, during recess, it happens that a clumsy boy with long, dark hair speaks to him.
When she answers, the other students look at her surprised; no one, apart from her, hears or sees the boy.
They think the shy girl is a weird dreamer, but Sarah K. knows she’s not dreaming.
She's awake and she sees and hears that boy, the same way she sees and hears the girl sitting on the bench next door.
You can even feel their presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, he likes the guy.
Sometimes she wonders if she's crazy.
He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and disappear.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When he is in class sometimes he cannot follow the lesson because the teacher – to his eyes and ears – is presenting a new classmate, while for the rest he explains the mathematical equations visibly and audibly.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
While waiting in the dark room for the sleep, which often comes late and is scarce, she does not know whether she is awake or dreaming, if the images she sees, the grimaces or the girl with bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, appear in front of her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, he yells at the figures.
She hasn't told her parents and friends anything, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is now 20 years old.
She passed selectivity last year and lives with her boyfriend.
The hallucinations have been gone for a year.
Ever since she got in touch over the Internet with psychologist Kasten, she knows she's not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art out of despair.
According to Kasten, when a person finds himself socially isolated or suffers a restriction of stimuli, it is very likely that after a while he will begin to have hallucinations.
I think the brain is unemployed and is in charge of seeking entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was little afraid of the other children and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he learned that the man he has been calling dad since he had use of reason is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, those affected like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain produces, which is why they seem so real.”
Kasten also classifies nighttime fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of an acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, psychically healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends his patients to appreciate their hallucinations as a special skill.
The boundary between sleep and hallucination
In this world too focused on the conscious, imaginary experiences are usually pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the clinic of psychiatry and psychotherapy at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also involves something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that subsequently can not differentiate from being awake.
Dream conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of oneself or the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with an imaginary world of one’s own that is decoupled from reality.
A form of boundary situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, there is a change of world, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an unbearable situation itself that our own capacity for creation allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich also describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a soul-saving action.
He was 49 when his conscience embarked on multi-day journeys after heart valve surgery with heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen immersed himself in a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he found himself prostrate in bed, an older man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot watching over his health.
It was seen in the early Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorbike kidnapped him in his home country, surfed over his hospital bed in the Alps with snow firn and ran into a Korean mobster.
It gives it all in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so describe your experience.
On the contrary, the memories of mental journeys are, many years later, much clearer, even in the irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intensive even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our daily experiences, adds the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychoses, hallucinations and narcotics use show how fragile the inner reproduction of the outer reality is, even when we are awake.
Every modification of the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality."
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
