Emergency braking aid is now mandatory
As with ABS antilock brakes and ESP stability control, emergency braking systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a lack period is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, by their way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by range.
The emergency braking assistant does this by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver’s footstep.
But it doesn’t always keep that pressure to the end.
According to a study by car components manufacturer Bosch, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident had not stepped on the brakes before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, demands the maximum of the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with this type of element, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater – it is estimated that one in four personal injury claims would be avoided – when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via a radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
