Online auction of accidented cars
Last October the Solera group bought Autoonline, an online platform for the sale of cars such as motorcycles or special accident vehicles.
The transaction involved a disbursement of 59.5 million euros for 85% of the company’s capital, which could be extended next year to the remaining 15%.
The objective of the acquisition was to offer more value-added services to its customers, with the possibility of accessing a huge international market.
This valuation and sales service is aimed exclusively at professionals in the sector, such as insurance companies, experts, rental companies, workshops, scrapshops and professional sellers who must register before starting to carry out operations.
This platform was created in 1996 in Germany and manages more than 650,000 operations throughout Europe, 500,000 of them in Germany.
Among its main markets are Spain, Greece, Poland and Turkey.
The website currently has more than 1,500 registered sellers and 4,000 experts.
3,000 ads are managed daily and about 100 new ads are included in the Spanish market every day.
Under Spanish law, a car whose frame number has been cancelled may not be re-circulated, but certain parts that are not damaged may be used as a replacement.
Cars with historical value can be registered even if they have been discharged after a difficult process.
Workshop budget in four steps
With the Auda-Workshop tool, the Audatex company guarantees that the user gets a budget in just four steps: identify the vehicle, search for the spare part, create a budget and generate a budget.
Ease of use is an essential constraint for these systems, especially to convince older professionals, who to a greater or lesser extent are usually more reluctant to use new management techniques.
The database includes 1,034 vehicles, which are 666 passenger cars, 109 off-roaders, 137 motorcycles, 78 vans and 44 trucks.
Of course, to use it you need a computer with an internet connection.
Once the model to be repaired is identified by its frame number, a real graphic image of the model in question appears and then the necessary spare is selected.
The user can include variables such as labor price, surcharges or discounts, and then print the quote to deliver to the customer.
AudaTaller is not a valuation tool like AudaPlus, but rather a catalog of references.
The main difference between the two systems is that the workshop-oriented one does not include estimated labor times.
The cost of using this tool for the workshop is 350 euros per year, which the customer can finance.
The Audatex company is currently working to make these images three-dimensional.
This is an innovation that mechanics see with very good eyes, as it will allow, for example, to select a door and turn it around to see the inner face.
